The '''flag of [[Bulgaria]]''' ({{lang-bg|знаме на България}}, {{IPA-mk|znamɛ nɐ bɐɫˈɡarijɐ|}}, ''zname na Bǎlgariya'') is a [[tricolour (flag)|tricolour]] consisting of three equal-sized horizontal bands of (from top to bottom) white, green, and red. The flag was first adopted after the [[Russo-Turkish War (1877–1878)|1877–1878 Russo-Turkish War]], when Bulgaria gained independence. The [[national flag]] at times was charged with the state emblem, especially during the [[People's Republic of Bulgaria|communist era]]. The current flag was re-established with the 1991 [[Constitution of Bulgaria]] and was confirmed in a 1998 law.

==History==
After the liberation of Bulgaria following the Russo-Turkish War in 1878, the flag was described in the [[Tarnovo Constitution]] of 1879 as follows:

{{cquote|Art. 23. The Bulgarian people's flag is three-coloured and consists of white, green and red colours, placed horizontally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infotel.bg/juen/arh/i4240002.htm |title=Tarnovo Constitution of 1879 |publisher=Juridical Encyclopedia |language=Bulgarian |accessdate=2007-09-15 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070911122019/http://www.infotel.bg/juen/arh/i4240002.htm |archivedate=2007-09-11 |df= }}</ref>}}

From 1946 until 1990 the [[Emblem of the People's Republic of Bulgaria|emblem]] of the [[People's Republic of Bulgaria]] was placed on the left side of the white stripe. It contained a lion within a wreath of wheat ears below a [[red star]] and above a ribbon bearing the date 9 September 1944, the day of [[Bulgarian coup d'état of 1944]] which led to the establishment of the [[People's Republic of Bulgaria]]. In 1971, it was changed so the ribbon bearing the years 681, the year of the establishment of the [[First Bulgarian Empire]] by [[Asparukh of Bulgaria|Asparukh]] and 1944.

Following the fall of communism in 1990, the then-enforced [[Zhivkov Constitution]] was amended so the flag can be reverted to the pre-communism era.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.informationbulgaria.com/bulgarian_flag.html |title=Understanding the Bulgarian Flag |publisher=Information Bulgaria |accessdate=2017-12-08}}</ref> The new [[Constitution of Bulgaria]], adopted in 1991, describes the Bulgarian flag as follows:

{{cquote|Art. 166. The flag of the Republic of Bulgaria shall be a tricolour: white, green and red from top, placed horizontally.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.bg/?page=const&lng=en |title=Constitution of the Republic of Bulgaria |publisher=National Assembly of the Republic of Bulgaria |accessdate=2007-09-15}}</ref>}}

A popular version of the flag, which has no official status, is also commonly known. It has the full coat of arms on the left of the flag, placed across the white and green fields only.<ref>[http://dariknews.bg/uploads/news_images/201306/photo_verybig_1107050.jpg Unofficial flag], taken from [http://dariknews.bg/view_article.php?article_id=1107050 2013 Bulgaria Summer Protests], ''Darik News'', 26 June 2013, and [https://c479107.ssl.cf2.rackcdn.com/files/26026/article/width668/ff8jnhxz-1372017632.jpg unofficial flag], taken from [http://theconversation.com/protests-in-bulgaria-the-unnoticed-uprising-15442 Protests in Bulgaria: the unnoticed uprising], ''TheConversation.com'', 24 Jun 2013. Both retrieved 27 Jun 2013.</ref>

==Flag law==
According to the Law for the State Seal and National Flag of the Republic of Bulgaria, promulgated on 24 April 1998:

{{cquote|Art. 15. (1) The national flag of the Republic of Bulgaria is a national symbol which expresses the independence and sovereignty of the Bulgarian state.

(2) The national flag of the Republic of Bulgaria is tricolour: white, green and red fields, placed horizontally from the top downwards. On fixing the national flag in a vertical situation of the carrying body the colours shall be arranged from left to right - white, green, red.

(3) The national flag is of a rectangular shape. The fields of the individual colours shall be equal in size and shall be situated along the horizontal of the rectangular.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.bg/?page=history&lng=en&hid=8 |title=Law for the State Seal and National Flag of the Republic of Bulgaria |publisher=National Assembly of the Republic |accessdate=2007-09-15 }}</ref>}}

