'''''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'''''{{efn|Known in Japan as {{nihongo|''Metaru Gia Soriddo Faibu Fantomu Pein''|メタルギアソリッドV ファントムペイン|extra="Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain"}}}} is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]] [[stealth game]] developed by [[Kojima Productions]] and published by [[Konami]]. It was released worldwide for [[Microsoft Windows]], [[PlayStation 3]], [[PlayStation 4]], [[Xbox 360]] and [[Xbox One]] on September 1, 2015. It is the ninth installment in the [[Metal Gear series|series]] that was directed, written and designed by [[Hideo Kojima]] following ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes]]'', a stand-alone prologue released the previous year, as well as his final work at Konami.

Set in 1984, nine years after the events of ''Ground Zeroes'' and a decade before the events of the original ''[[Metal Gear (video game)|Metal Gear]]'', the story follows mercenary leader [[Venom Snake|Punished "Venom" Snake]] as he ventures into [[Soviet Union|Soviet]]-occupied [[Afghanistan]] and the [[Angola]]–[[Zaire]] border region to exact revenge on the people who destroyed his forces and came close to killing him during the climax of ''Ground Zeroes''. It carries over the tagline of ''Tactical Espionage Operations'' first used in ''[[Metal Gear Solid: Peace Walker]]''.

''The Phantom Pain'' was critically acclaimed upon release, with its gameplay drawing praise for featuring a variety of [[Game mechanics|mechanics]] and interconnected systems which allow a high degree of player freedom in approaching objectives. While the story was acknowledged for its emotional power and exploration of mature [[Theme (narrative)|themes]], it drew criticism from some critics for its lack of focus, with further scrutiny over its second half and ending that left several plot points unresolved; this was linked to conclusive evidence of removed content, which led some to suggest that the game was released unfinished. Despite this, ''The Phantom Pain'' received perfect review scores from several publications and was described by some critics to be the greatest stealth game of all time. A complete edition that bundles ''The Phantom Pain'' and ''Ground Zeroes'' together, titled ''Metal Gear Solid V: The Definitive Experience'', was released in October 2016.

== Gameplay ==
''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'' is an [[Action-adventure game|action-adventure]], [[Stealth game|stealth]] game in which players take the role of Punished "Venom" Snake from a [[Virtual camera system#Third-person view|third-person perspective]] in an [[open world]] environment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2013-06-10-metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-reveals-open-world-gameplay|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain reveals open world gameplay|first=Jeffery|last=Matulef|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=October 6, 2013|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> The gameplay elements were largely unchanged from ''Ground Zeroes'', meaning that players will have to sneak from several points in the game world, avoiding enemy guards, and remaining undetected.<ref name="Bino">{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamer.com/features/article/why_metal_gear_solid_5_the_phantom_pain_isnt_just_a_bigger_ground_zeroes_2.html|title=Why Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain isn't just a bigger Ground Zeroes|first=Steven|last=Burns|work=VideoGamer.com|date=June 11, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150905141052/http://www.videogamer.com/features/article/why_metal_gear_solid_5_the_phantom_pain_isnt_just_a_bigger_ground_zeroes_2.html#|archive-date=2015-09-05|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> Included in Snake's repertoire are binoculars, maps, a variety of weapons, explosives, and stealth-based items such as cardboard boxes and decoys.<ref name="Bino"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/metal-gear-solid-5-delivers-spectacular-open-world-stealth/|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 delivers spectacular open world stealth|first=Matthew|last=Pellett|date=June 9, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015|work=[[PC Gamer]]}}</ref> Following one of the series traditions, ''The Phantom Pain'' encourages players to progress through the game without killing, using non-lethal weapons such as tranquilizer darts to subdue enemies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/metal-gear-solid-gets-bigger-and-better-in-the-phantom-pain/|title=Metal Gear Solid gets bigger and better in The Phantom Pain|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=July 23, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Players may traverse the game world with vehicles such as jeeps and tanks, in addition to traveling on foot or on horseback, and as certain locations are mountainous,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2459312,00.asp|title=Eyes On With 'Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'|first=Jeffery|last=L. Wilson|work=[[PC Magazine]]|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> occasionally, players can opt to go [[rock climbing]] as a shortcut.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/why-snake-is-the-best-climber-in-video-game-history-1636633722|title=Why Snake Is The Best Climber In Video Game History|first=Mark|last=Serrels|work=[[Kotaku]]|date=September 18, 2014|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> They may call for helicopter support against enemy soldiers or request airstrikes that can bomb the target area or change the current weather.<ref name="companion">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2015/06/10/19-awesome-details-we-noticed-in-metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain|title=19 Awesome Details We Noticed In Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain|first=Jose|last=Otero|work=[[IGN]]|date=June 10, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Snake can call on AI companions&mdash;including [[Quiet (Metal Gear)|Quiet]], a silent female sniper with supernatural abilities; D-Horse, a horse with a customizable saddle for carrying more equipment in the field; D-Walker, a manned, highly agile mobile weapons platform that can provide heavy weapons support; and D-Dog, a wolf pup raised and trained on the new Mother Base to assist him in the field.<ref name="GS_MGSV-Wolf">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/metal-gear-solid-v-introduces-snakes-one-eyed-wolf/1100-6422449/|title=Metal Gear Solid V Introduces Snake's One-Eyed Wolf Buddy|last=Maiberg|first=Emanuel|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=20 September 2014|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref> The companions' abilities and their effectiveness will depend on the player's relationship with them.<ref name="companion"/> There is a large emphasis based on tactics in ''The Phantom Pain''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/09/03/metal-gear-solid-5-phantom-pain-best-tactics/|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain - the 11 best tactics you're not using right now - VG247|author=|date=3 September 2015|website=vg247.com}}</ref>

As in ''Peace Walker'', ''The Phantom Pain'' features a base-building system that allows players to develop weapons and items from their home base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2014-06-11-managing-mother-base-in-metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain|title=Managing Mother Base in Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain|first=Wesley|last=Yin-Poole|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=June 11, 2014|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Recruitment of enemy soldiers and [[prisoner of war|prisoners]] has also returned for this purpose, allowing the base to grow through organization. The player is given the option to access their base from their real-life smartphones and other devices via a companion app.<ref name="demo">{{cite news|title=Metal Gear Solid Ground Zeroes to feature base-building, will support multiple devices|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-09-27-metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-to-feature-base-building-will-support-multiple-devices|first=Jonathan|last=Toyad|work=[[Eurogamer]]|date=27 September 2012|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref> Unlike in ''Peace Walker'' where players can only see Mother Base from the air, they can control Snake as he explores the complex on foot. The [[Fulton surface-to-air recovery system]], an item introduced into gameplay in ''Peace Walker,'' returns as well, with players able to transport captured soldiers and other objects such as animals and vehicles back to Mother Base.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2014/06/12/recruiting-goats-and-researching-cardboard-in-metal-gear-solid-5/|title=Recruiting goats and researching cardboard in Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain|first=Xav|last=De Mato|work=[[Joystiq]]|date=June 12, 2014|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Money for upgrading Mother Base's defenses and technology can be collected from objects found all over the map, such as diamonds, shipping containers, and special blueprint boxes,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/how-mother-bases-units-help-snake-mgs-5/|title=How Mother Base’s units help Snake in MGS 5|work=[[GamesRadar]]|date=June 28, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> as well as sending recruited soldiers on combat missions around the world. The income is invested in upgrades to the appearance and abilities, weapons and equipment of Snake, his AI companions, and vehicles. For example, Snake's prosthetic arm can be modified with a taser, echolocation function, or remote controls that allow it to fly as a drone.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEqdbKg3K8Y|title=Metal Gear Solid V - African Jungle Gameplay w/ Dev Commentary|date=25 September 2014|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=MGSV: TPP - Freedom of Infiltration Gameplay Demo|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=pqu0nRb0puM?t=1365|website=YouTube|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref>

The enemy AI has improved in terms of situational awareness. If players frequently use particular weapons or tactics to subdue enemy soldiers, this will see the enemy increase in numbers and be outfitted with better equipment; for example, the frequent use of headshots will see enemy soldiers don metal helmets to make targeting the head harder.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/14/gamescom-2014-metal-gear-solid-5s-tower-defence-style-multiplayer|title=Gamescom 2014: Metal Gear Solid 5's Tower Defense Style Multiplayer|first=Alex|last=Simmons|work=[[IGN]]|date=August 13, 2014|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref>

The game has a dynamic weather system and day-night cycle that runs in real-time.<ref name="Gamespot">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-includes-mother-base-day-night-cycle-6397373 |title=Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes includes Mother Base, day/night cycle |last=Cocker |first=Guy |date=28 September 2012 |accessdate=15 October 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121016015329/http://www.gamespot.com/news/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-includes-mother-base-day-night-cycle-6397373 |archivedate=October 16, 2012 }}</ref> The cycle is able to be fast-forwarded when Snake lights a "Phantom Cigar", a type of [[electronic cigarette|electronic cigar]]; a digital silver [[Seiko]] [[watch]] panel appears on screen to denote time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-15-hours-in-af/1100-6427900/|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain - 15 Hours in Afghanistan|first=Peter|last=Brown|work=[[GameSpot]]|date=June 9, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> The passage of time enables players to analyze the movement of marked enemy forces in the area, such as shifts in sentry patrols and individual patrol routes. Weather effects, such as sandstorms and rain, affects the gameplay environment by reducing visibility or masking the sound of footsteps.<ref name="africa">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/everything-we-learned-from-the-metal-gear-solid-5-/1100-6422426/|title=Everything We Learned From the Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain TGS 2014 Trailer|last=Hindes|first=Daniel|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=19 September 2014|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref>

A game design direction allows the player to choose in what order the story events take place by selecting missions in any order they like, and yet still "understand the encompassing message by the end".<ref name="Nyxus">{{cite web|url=http://metalgearsolid.nl/?p=4571 |title=Interviews from Dubai: Kojima on Gray Fox game, story telling in Ground Zeroes, next gen and more |last=Nyxus |date=20 January 2013 |publisher=Metal Gear Solid Unofficial Site |accessdate=20 January 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208224458/http://metalgearsolid.nl/?p=4571 |archivedate=February 8, 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://saudigamer.com/2013/01/19/hideo-kojima-meeting/|title=My meeting with one of the greatest game directors: Hideo Kojima|last=Dubayan|date=19 January 2013|publisher=Saudi Gamer|accessdate=20 January 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130515102539/http://saudigamer.com/2013/01/19/hideo-kojima-meeting |archive-date=15 May 2013}}</ref>

Kojima spoke about the restrictive nature of previous ''Metal Gear Solid'' titles, saying that they "set [the player] on one rail to get from point A to point B, with a certain amount of freedom between". In stark contrast, ''The Phantom Pain'' offers players new ways of traversal and sneaking methods, such as taking a motorcycle, plane or helicopter to the mission area (however, usage of the former two vehicles was later dropped during development). Players are able to traverse the game world or deploy directly to landing zones that allow for different approaches. A video published after the E3 2015 convention showcased this, with the same mission played four times in a number of different ways: with the player opting for stealth, launching a direct assault via helicopter gunship, attempting to assassinate a target with a sniper rifle, and smuggling an explosive device into an enemy base by way of an unsuspecting patrol vehicle crew.<ref>{{cite web|title=MGSV: TPP - Freedom of Infiltration Gameplay Demo|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=pqu0nRb0puM?t=27m19s|website=YouTube|accessdate=1 August 2015}}</ref> The player's actions affect the wider game world; for example, sabotaging a radar installation will open up new entry points.<ref>{{cite web|last=Sinha|first=Ravi|title=Metal Gear Solid Ground Zeroes: "Ultimate Goal is To Give Players More Freedom"|url=http://gamingbolt.com/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-ultimate-goal-is-to-give-players-more-freedom|publisher=GamingBolt|accessdate=15 March 2013}}</ref> The playable world in ''The Phantom Pain'' is two hundred times larger than that of ''Ground Zeroes'', featuring a variety of climate conditions and environments. This allows the players to freely roam the map while proceeding to either story missions or sidequests, as in other games with [[nonlinear gameplay]]. In addition, players who have previously played ''Ground Zeroes'' are able to import save data into ''The Phantom Pain'' and gain special perks.<ref name="Famitsu feature">{{cite web|date=2014-04-10|url=http://gematsu.com/2014/04/famitsu-feature-truth-rumors-2014|title=Famitsu feature: The Truth of the Rumors 2014|publisher=Gematsu}}</ref>

=== Multiplayer ===
''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'' includes two multiplayer modes: first, the new ''[[Metal Gear Online]]'', developed by Kojima Productions' newly formed Los Angeles division (now known as Konami Los Angeles Studio).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/414360/interviews/e3-interview-kojima-on-mgs-5|title=E3 Interview}}</ref> The first footage for multiplayer was revealed in December 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/06/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-multiplayer-revealed|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain Multiplayer Revealed|work=IGN.com|accessdate=March 19, 2015}}</ref><ref name="polygon-kojimaremoved">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/3/19/8257283/metal-gear-solid-konami-branding|title=Metal Gear Solid creator's involvement in series questioned, Konami removes branding|website=Polygon|accessdate=19 March 2015}}</ref> While originally set for launch alongside the release of ''The Phantom Pain'', ''Metal Gear Online'' was postponed to October 6 for consoles and January 2016 for Microsoft Windows.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 5's Multiplayer Won't Be Available at Launch|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/metal-gear-solid-5s-multiplayer-wont-be-available-/1100-6429413/|last=Newhouse|first=Alex|publisher=[[GameSpot]]|date=August 3, 2015|accessdate=August 3, 2015}}</ref>

The second multiplayer mode is an extension of the Mother Base base-building feature. Players are able to expand their operations to include "Forward Operating Bases" which can be used to generate resources and income for the single-player campaign.<ref name="GIFOBMGO3">{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/games/metal_gear_solid_v_the_phantom_pain/b/playstation4/archive/2015/06/18/new-intel-for-metal-gear-online.aspx|title=[Update] The Real Intel On Metal Gear V's Forward Operating Bases|first=Matthew|last=Kato|work=[[Game Informer]]|date=June 18, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> These facilities can be attacked by other players, making a player-versus-player mode available whereby the attacking team attempts to steal resources and/or soldiers and the defending team tries to protect the Forward Operating Base from the intruder. Defenders are able to call on their friends to aid in the defense, especially if their Forward Operating Base is attacked during a story mission.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/08/06/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-mmo-fob-invade-players/|title=Invade other players’ worlds in FOB, Metal Gear Solid 5’s "MMO mode"|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|work=[[VG247]]|date=August 6, 2015|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> Players are able to customize the security, staffing, and layout of their Forward Operating Bases, allowing for a large number of compound configurations. Following the success or failure of the intrusion, the location of the attacking player's Forward Operating Base is revealed to the defending player;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/everything-you-need-to-know-about-metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-s-mother-base-3423047|title=Everything you need to know about Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain's Mother Base|first=Mike|last=Splechta|accessdate=August 24, 2015}}</ref> however, defending players can only launch a retaliatory strike if the attacker was discovered during their infiltration. The Forward Operating Base feature is an entirely separate multiplayer experience to ''Metal Gear Online''<ref name="GIFOBMGO3"/> and is also needed to increase the number of combat units the player can deploy.

During development, Kojima Productions and Konami attracted criticism for their decision to include [[microtransactions]]; a system that allows players to pay for access to content in the game. However, a spokesperson for Kojima Productions confirmed that the system was included to benefit players who may not have the time to complete the game, given its scale, and that no content would be available exclusively through microtransactions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/metal-gear-solid-5-gets-info-about-bases-microtran/1100-6429588/|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 Gets Info About Bases, Microtransactions, Online Functionality|first=Alex|last=Newhouse|work=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> Further controversy emerged following the publication of an early review claiming that the Forward Operating Base mode was behind a paywall,<ref name="GSpot" /> which Konami refuted saying that microtransactions acted as an [[Pay to win|accelerator]] rather than a paywall.<ref name="refuted">{{cite news|url=http://www.pcgamer.com/mgs-5-the-phantom-pains-multiplayer-is-not-behind-a-paywall/|title=''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain''{{'s}} multiplayer is not behind a paywall|first=Phil|last=Savage|work=[[PC Gamer]]|date=26 August 2015|accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref>

