At [[E3 2013]], Konami confirmed that actor [[Kiefer Sutherland]] would provide Snake's voice and motion capture work for the game,<ref>{{cite web|last=Romano|first=Sal|title=Metal Gear Solid V clip teases Snake’s new voice actor|url=http://gematsu.com/2013/05/metal-gear-solid-v-clip-teases-snakes-new-voice-actor|publisher=Gematsu|accessdate=3 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Brian |title=Snake’s voice actor in Metal Gear Solid V to be revealed during Konami’s pre-E3 show |url=http://gamingeverything.com/48904/snakes-voice-actor-in-metal-gear-solid-v-to-be-revealed-during-konamis-pre-e3-show/ |publisher=GamingEverything |accessdate=3 June 2013 }}{{dead link|date=June 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Staff|title=Konami’s pre-E3 stream: Kiefer Sutherland Playing Snake in Metal Gear Solid 5|url=http://www.vg247.com/2013/06/06/metal-gear-solid-5-castlevania-los-2-pes-2014-to-feature-in-konamis-pre-e3-stream-tonight/|publisher=VG24/7|accessdate=6 June 2013}}</ref> taking a role over voice actor [[David Hayter]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Beloved Solid Snake Voice Actor Says He Wasn’t Asked to Be in Metal Gear Solid V|url=http://kotaku.com/beloved-solid-snake-voice-actor-says-he-wasn-t-asked-to-461256492|first=Evan|last=Narcisse|work=[[Kotaku]]|publisher=[[Gawker Media]]|date=27 March 2013|accessdate=27 March 2013}}</ref> Kojima's reason for replacing Hayter was to "have a more subdued performance expressed through subtle facial movements and tone of voice rather than words", and that he "needed someone who could genuinely convey both the facial and vocal qualities of a man in his late 40s". Hollywood producer and director [[Avi Arad]] suggested to Kojima that Sutherland could fulfill his requirements.<ref>{{cite web|last=Goldfarb|first=Andrew|title=Kiefer Sutherland Playing Snake in Metal Gear Solid V|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2013/06/06/kiefer-sutherland-playing-snake-in-metal-gear-solid-v|publisher=IGN|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref><ref name="YouTube_MGSV-BTS">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5yuC1h7LGKc|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 - Behind The Scenes|work=[[YouTube]]|publisher=GamesHQMedia|date=6 June 2013|accessdate=24 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: Kiefer Sutherland = More Cutscenes - IGN Conversation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Lh0gnSerOA|website=[[YouTube]]|publisher=IGN|accessdate=23 June 2014}}</ref> [[Akio Ōtsuka]] was unaffected by this casting change and continued to voice Snake in the Japanese version.<ref name="hideradio_20130621">{{cite web|url=http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog/2013/06/000477.html|title= ヒデラジE3スペシャル（後篇） 【通算第315回】 （13.06.21） |language=Japanese}}</ref> On March 4, 2015, Kojima revealed that Snake would have less dialogue in ''The Phantom Pain'' than previous installments. The reasoning behind it was to make Snake come across as an extension to the player and that he "will act based on [player's actions] rather than doing things like making spontaneous comments or flirting with women."<ref name="SpeakMuch2015"/>

Other members of the voice cast include [[Troy Baker]] as [[Revolver Ocelot|Ocelot]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Troy Baker Confirmed as Ocelot in Metal Gear Solid V|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2013/06/13/troy-baker-confirmed-as-ocelot-in-metal-gear-solid-v|first=Luke|last=Reilly|work=IGN|date=12 June 2013|accessdate=13 June 2013}}</ref> [[Jay Tavare]] as Code Talker,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=568156443226108&set=a.127417547300002.10366.127417027300054&type=1|title=Jay Tavare's Facebook}}</ref> [[James Horan (actor)|James Horan]] as Skull Face, [[Robin Atkin Downes]] as Kazuhira Miller, [[Christopher Randolph]] as Dr. Emmerich<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=elMikUGFfqw|title=MGSV The Phantom Pain - Mission: Ground Zeroes - Opening (en)|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> and Piers Stubbs as [[Liquid Snake|Eli]]. The Japanese dub features [[Tomokazu Sugita]] as Miller, [[Hideyuki Tanaka]] as Emmerich, Takaya Hashi as Skull Face, [[Satoshi Mikami]] as Ocelot, [[Osamu Saka]] (whose previous roles include Sergei Gurlukovich in ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'' and The End in ''[[Metal Gear Solid 3: Snake Eater]]'') as Code Talker,<ref name=hideradio_20130612/><ref name="twitter_20140807">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Kojima_Hideo/status/497344512914501632/photo/1|title=Twitter / Kojima_Hideo: MGSや小島作品ではお馴染みの阪脩さん。コードトーカーと対面。 |language=Japanese}}</ref> and Yūtarō Honjō as Eli.<ref name="twitter_20140929">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/HIDEO_KOJIMA_EN/status/516526929344610305|title=HIDEO_KOJIMA on Twitter: "Had VO session. Satoshi Mikami(Ocelot), Tomokazu Sugita (Kaz), Akio Otsuka(Snake), Yutaro Honjo(Eli) and me(Hideo)."}}</ref> Dutch-born model [[Stefanie Joosten]] provides the likeness, voice and motion capture for the new heroine Quiet,<ref name="hideradio_20130612">{{cite web|url=http://www.kjp.konami.jp/gs/hideoblog/2013/06/000476.html|title= ヒデラジE3スペシャル（前篇） 【通算第314回】 （13.06.12） |language=Japanese}}</ref> a mute sniper with supernatural abilities who may assist Snake on missions depending on the player's actions during a certain mission.<ref name="gamespot20140925">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/metal-gear-solid-5-exclusive-kojima-q-a-on-the-tgs/1100-6422389/|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: Exclusive Kojima Q&A on the TGS Demo (now in 1080p)|website=[[GameSpot]]}}</ref> She also provides the vocals for "Quiet's Theme".

=== Synopsis ===
In 1984, nine years after the events of ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes]]'', [[Big Boss (Metal Gear)|Big Boss]] awakens from a coma in a hospital in [[Cyprus]]. [[Quiet (Metal Gear)|Quiet]], a Cipher assassin, tries to kill him, but Big Boss is rescued by a heavily bandaged man called Ishmael. The pair escapes the hospital while evading pursuit from Cipher's soldiers and two superhumans, [[Psycho Mantis|Tretij Rebenok, the "Third Child"]] and [[Colonel Volgin|the "Man on Fire"]]. Although Big Boss loses sight of Ishmael, he is recovered by his ally [[Revolver Ocelot]] and brought aboard [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Diamond Dogs|Diamond Dogs]], a new mercenary group founded by [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Master Miller|Kazuhira Miller]] on an offshore platform near [[Seychelles]].

Big Boss adopts the code name "[[Venom Snake]]" and begins searching for Cipher. During his journey, Snake becomes involved in the [[Soviet–Afghan War|Soviet-Afghan]] and the [[Angolan Civil War|Angolan Civil]] Wars, and he recruits Quiet, who no longer speaks and has gained superhuman abilities; scientist [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Huey|Dr. Huey Emmerich]]; and [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Code Talker|Code Talker]], a [[Navajo people|Navajo]] expert on parasites forced to work for Cipher. [[Liquid Snake|Eli]], a British child believed to be [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Les Enfants Terrible|a clone of Snake]], who leads a band of child soldiers is brought to the base after an operation. Though there is speculation into whether or not he is Big Boss's son, a DNA test confirms that Venom Snake and Eli are not genetically related.

Snake learns that Cipher's leader Major Zero was usurped and [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#XOF|XOF]], a rogue faction of Cipher, was responsible for destroying MSF. XOF's leader [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Skull Face|Skull Face]] considers Cipher's plan to unite the world for peace as the same as making it culturally American, obliterating other cultures. To avoid this, he intends to release a unique parasite that kills anyone who speaks [[English language|English]]. A modified parasite was used to give Quiet and Skull Face's elite soldiers, the Skulls, their unusual abilities. After releasing the English strain parasite, Skull Face plans to make nuclear weapons available to as many groups as he can, believing that [[Deterrence theory|nuclear deterrence]] will stop the weapons actually being used, attaining world peace while still protecting the integrity of each culture. However, he will secretly retain remote control of the weapons. Skull Face intends to use the threat of the latest Metal Gear system, known as ST-84 "Sahelanthropus", to make nuclear weapons desirable again, but as he cannot get it to function, he is dependent on the Third Child's psychic abilities to manipulate it.

During a test, the Third Child turns against Skull Face, having Sahelanthropus seriously wound him and crush the Man on Fire. Although Snake defeats the Metal Gear, he is only able to recover one of Skull Face's three parasite vials; one goes missing and the other is taken by the Third Child and given to Eli. Skull Face is left to die by Snake and Miller but Huey executes him. The Diamond Dogs return to their base with Sahelanthropus. Following their return, Eli, the Third Child, and the child soldiers steal Sahelanthropus and flee the base. It transpires that the Third Child was not consciously working for Skull Face, but his psychic powers enthralled him to the will of the most vengeful person nearby, meaning Sahelanthropus's attack was instigated by Eli.

An epidemic of parasites occurs on base forcing Snake to personally kill many of his own men to contain it. To honor them, he has their cremated remains turned into diamonds to carry into battle. Huey is accused of causing the epidemic while attempting to mutate the parasites to sell as weapons. Alongside suspicion of his role in MSF's destruction, and evidence that he murdered his wife [[List of characters in the Metal Gear series#Strangelove|Dr. Strangelove]] while arguing over using [[Otacon|their son]] in experiments, Snake exiles him from Diamond Dogs. Following this event, Quiet disappears in Afghanistan. Code Talker reveals that Quiet was infected with the English strain parasite with the intention of joining Diamond Dogs in order to spread it, but her allegiance shifted to Snake and so she remained silent to prevent an outbreak. Huey's mutation of the parasite convinced Quiet that she could not guarantee the safety of Diamond Dogs. Snake finds Quiet captured by Soviet soldiers and frees her only to be attacked an onslaught of armored vehicles. They defeat the wave but as another one approaches they are forced to hide in a sandstorm. Quiet is then forced to speak to summon help when Snake is bitten by a venomous snake. She disappears into the desert to avoid causing another epidemic.

It is later revealed that Venom Snake is not actually Big Boss but a loyal MSF medic caught in the same explosion that injured the real Big Boss, Ishmael. During his coma, the medic was transformed into a second Big Boss via [[plastic surgery]] and [[hypnotherapy]] to serve as a decoy for the actual Big Boss while he wages a covert war against Cipher. On behalf of the real Big Boss, Venom Snake goes on to set the events of the [[Metal Gear (video game)|Outer Heaven uprising]] in motion and dies at the hands of [[Solid Snake]]. The original Big Boss resurfaces during the [[Metal Gear 2: Solid Snake|Zanzibar Land disturbance]]. Miller and Ocelot discuss Big Boss' plans to create Outer Heaven. While Ocelot remains supportive, Miller is disgusted at his former ally's deception but agrees to continue assisting Venom Snake and Big Boss's sons in hopes of contributing to the real Big Boss's downfall.

== Development ==
[[File:Kojipro GDC recruitment poster.png|thumb|200px|left|A recruiting poster, based on the famous [[Lord Kitchener Wants You|recruitment poster]], used at [[Game Developers Conference|GDC]] 2012]]

In February 2012, a site owned by Konami, "Development Without Borders", promoted development for a new ''Metal Gear'' title, for "The "next" MGS". The site was recruiting staff for the 2012 [[Game Developers Conference|GDC]] pavilion in March, and requested applications for several positions for the latest ''Metal Gear Solid'' targeted for "high-end consoles" and "next-gen Fox engine".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-02-22-next-metal-gear-solid-targets-high-end-consoles-next-gen-fox-engine|title=Next Metal Gear Solid targets "high-end consoles", "next-gen" Fox engine|last=Purchese|first=Robert|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|date=22 February 2012|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/02/22/kojima-productions-hiring-for-next-metal-gear-solid|title=Kojima Productions Hiring For "Next" Metal Gear Solid|last=Reilly|first=Luke|publisher=IGN|date=22 February 2012|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref> As the year went on, screenshots and videos of the newly announced [[Fox Engine]] were unveiled by the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2012-03-02-hideo-kojima-shows-off-impressive-fox-engine-screenshots|title=Hideo Kojima shows off impressive Fox Engine screenshots|last=Yin-Poole|first=Wesley|date=2 March 2012|publisher=EuroGamer.net|accessdate=4 February 2013}}</ref> This media demonstrated many random settings and characters, although none related to the ''Metal Gear'' series. Certain screenshots, however, were noted to feature a character who resembled the Big Boss character of ''Metal Gear'', walking up to a [[Stryker]] [[Armoured fighting vehicle|AFV]] previously seen in ''Metal Gear Solid 4''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/37720/Kojima_Inspires_With_Fox_Engine_Creative_Vision_At_USC.php#.URAvUaVX3Sg|title=Kojima Inspires With Fox Engine, Creative Vision At USC|last=McGarvey|first=Sterling|date=6 October 2011|publisher=Gamasutra|accessdate=4 February 2013}}</ref>

Konami unveiled ''[[Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes|Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes]]'' at a private function celebrating the twenty-fifth anniversary of the ''Metal Gear'' series on August 30, 2012. The game later made its public debut two days later at the 2012 [[Penny Arcade Expo]].<ref name="Gamers Hell">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamershell.com/news_142644.html|title=Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes PAX Prime 2012 Trailer|date=3 September 2012|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> Kojima revealed very little detail about the project at the time other than it was a prologue to ''Metal Gear Solid V'',<ref name="VG24/7">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2012/09/03/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-is-a-prologue-coming-to-ps3-xbox-360/|title=Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes is a "prologue", coming to PS3, Xbox 360|last=Hillier|first=Brenna|date=3 September 2012|accessdate=27 November 2012}}</ref> and that it would be the first game to use the [[Fox Engine]], a [[game engine]] developed by Kojima Productions.<ref>{{cite news|title=Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes shows off Fox Engine and possible open-world elements |url=http://uk.gamespot.com/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes/previews/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-shows-off-fox-engine-shine-and-possible-open-world-elements-6393924/ |first=Jonathan |last=Toyad |work=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=30 August 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120902084914/http://uk.gamespot.com/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes/previews/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-shows-off-fox-engine-shine-and-possible-open-world-elements-6393924/ |archivedate=2 September 2012}}</ref> In January 2013, Kojima revealed that ''Ground Zeroes'' would be the first title in the series to be subtitled in [[Arabic language|Arabic]], a feature the team had planned for previous games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.at7addak.com/en/Articles/226681/Features/PS3/Hideo-Kojima-Interview |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130215034654/http://www.at7addak.com/en/Articles/226681/Features/PS3/Hideo-Kojima-Interview |dead-url=yes |archive-date=15 February 2013 |title=Hideo Kojima Interview |last=Rabbit |date=20 January 2013 |publisher=At7addak |accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref> He also confirmed that the length of the cutscenes was reduced, as he believed that long cutscenes had become outdated.<ref name="Nyxus"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.youtharabia.com/gaming/one-on-one-with-hideo-kojima/ |title=One on One with Hideo Kojima |last=Oommen |first=Daniel |date=19 January 2013 |publisher=Youth Arabia |accessdate=20 January 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130122015109/http://www.youtharabia.com/gaming/one-on-one-with-hideo-kojima/ |archivedate=January 22, 2013 }}</ref>

In an interview with [[VG247]], Kojima expressed concerns over whether or not ''Ground Zeroes'' would be released. He claimed that his aim was to target taboos and mature themes, which he considered to be "quite risky", adding that his roles as creator and producer were in conflict with one another; as creator, Kojima wanted to take the risk of exploring themes that might alienate audiences, but as producer, he had to be able to tone down the content in order to sell as many copies of the game as possible. Ultimately, the role of creator won out, and Kojima described his approach as "prioritizing creativity over sales".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2013/02/22/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-will-tackle-many-taboos-may-not-release/|title=Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes will tackle many taboos, may not release in its current state|last=Akerman|first=Nick|date=22 February 2013|publisher=VG247|accessdate=22 February 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalgearsolidtv.com/2013/02/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-may-not.html|title=Metal Gear Solid Ground Zeroes - May Not Release In Its Current State And New Spin-offs, Possibly With The Boss|date=22 February 2013|publisher=MGSTV|accessdate=22 February 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225202222/http://www.metalgearsolidtv.com/2013/02/metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes-may-not.html|archivedate=25 February 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latestnewsexplorer.com/mgs-ground-zeroes-tackles-lots-of-taboos/|title=Konami: Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes Tackles Lots of Taboos, Risky To Be Released|last=MoStWaNteD|date=22 February 2013|publisher=Latest News Explorer|accessdate=22 February 2013}}</ref>

[[File:MGS5 E3 2013 poster.jpg|thumb|Poster distributed in E3 2013, with visual effects by Kyle Cooper.]]
At the [[Spike Video Game Awards]] in December 2012, a teaser trailer for a game known as ''The Phantom Pain'' was shown, credited to a new Swedish developer known as Moby Dick Studio, and was described as being "100% gameplay". Allegedly led by Joakim Mogren, the studio's mission statement read that it aimed to "deliver an uncompromising, exciting, and touching game experience to people all around the globe."<ref name="Gamespot2">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/news/the-phantom-pain-revealed-6401275 |title=The Phantom Pain revealed |last=Makuch |first=Eddie |publisher=[[GameSpot]] |date=7 December 2012 |accessdate=8 December 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121209075903/http://www.gamespot.com/news/the-phantom-pain-revealed-6401275 |archivedate=December 9, 2012 }}</ref> After the presentation, commentators speculated that ''The Phantom Pain'' was actually a ''Metal Gear'' game, noting the protagonist's resemblance to [[Big Boss (Metal Gear)|Big Boss]], graphics similar to those produced by the Fox Engine, the quote "V has come to" at the end of the trailer, and that the title ''Metal Gear Solid V'' fits in the [[negative space]] and indentations of the game's logo when using the same font.<ref name="Info">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2012/12/08/the-phantom-pain-metal-gear-solid-v|title=The Phantom Pain = Metal Gear Solid V?|last=Moriarty|first=Colin|publisher=IGN|date=7 December 2012|accessdate=8 December 2012}}</ref><ref name="forbes">{{cite news|last=Evangelho|first=Jason|title='The Phantom Pain' Is Kojima's Viral Teaser for 'Metal Gear Solid: Ground Zeroes'|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jasonevangelho/2012/12/07/the-phantom-pain-is-kojimas-viral-teaser-for-metal-gear-solid-ground-zeroes/|publisher=[[Forbes.com|Forbes]]|date=7 December 2012|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref> The name "Joakim" was an anagram of "Kojima", the [[domain name]] for the studio's website had only been registered about two weeks prior to the announcement, and that several people wearing Moby Dick Studio shirts were sitting in a VIP area intended for Konami staff.<ref name="Info" /><ref name="joystiq">{{cite web|last=Mallory|first=Jordan|title=The Phantom Pain speculation round-up: Metal Gear?!|url=http://www.joystiq.com/2012/12/08/the-phantom-pain-speculation-round-up-metal-gea|publisher=Joystiq|date=8 December 2012|accessdate=9 December 2012}}</ref> Hideo Kojima stated he was impressed by the trailer and how Mogren was inspired by ''Metal Gear''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://me.ign.com/en/feature/7036/Hideo-Kojima-Talks-MGR-FOX-Engine-and-Phantom-Pain|title=Hideo Kojima Talks MGR, FOX Engine, and Phantom Pain|last=Abu Nahel|first=Hakim|publisher=IGN|date=1 January 2013|accessdate=21 March 2013}}</ref>

An actor playing a heavily bandaged Mogren appeared in an interview on the March 14, 2013 episode of ''[[GameTrailers TV with Geoff Keighley|GameTrailers TV]]''; while stating that he could not reveal many details, he confirmed that more details about ''The Phantom Pain'' would be revealed at the upcoming Game Developers Conference, and showed a series of screenshots on an [[iPad]] to the show's host [[Geoff Keighley]]. After Keighley pointed out the Fox Engine logo in the screenshots, Mogren appeared nervous and the segment abruptly ended.<ref name="The Phantom Pain runs on Fox Engine">{{cite web|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/2m4qao/the-phantom-pain-joakim-mogren-interview|title=The Phantom Pain Video - Joakim Mogren Interview|publisher=[[GameTrailers]]|date=15 March 2013|accessdate=24 March 2013}}</ref>

On March 27, 2013, at GDC 2013, Kojima confirmed that his studio was behind the trailer, and announced that ''Metal Gear Solid V'' would be two separate games; ''Ground Zeroes'' would now serve as a prologue for the main game, which was officially announced as ''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain''.<ref name="groundzeroesseperate-gamespot">{{cite web|title=Ground Zeroes and Phantom Pain two different games|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/ground-zeroes-and-phantom-pain-two-different-games/1100-6406157/|website=GameSpot|publisher=CBS Interactive|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref><ref name="cvg-phantompain">{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain revealed|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/398237/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-revealed/|publisher=CVG.com|accessdate=27 March 2013}}</ref> He subsequently presented a trailer for the game and showcased the [[Fox Engine]].<ref name="vg247-phantompainreveal">{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain – Kojima speaks|url=http://www.vg247.com/2013/03/27/metal-gear-ground-zeroes-through-the-eyes-of-a-fox/|website=VG24/7|accessdate=3 March 2015}}</ref> The trailer featured the song "Not Your Kind of People" from [[Garbage (band)|Garbage]]'s 2012 [[Not Your Kind of People|album of the same name]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/metal-gear-solid-v-is-official-fox-vs-xof-update-t-461177345|title=Metal Gear Solid V Is Official - FOX vs. XOF (UPDATE: Trailer added)|publisher=Kotaku|date=27 March 2013|accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Kojima_Hideo/status/317195455392002049/photo/1 |title=Hideo Kojima on Twitter: Many people I met at party had already downloaded the song "Not your kind of people/Garbage", that I used in my MGS5 trailer. I have it in my iPod...|publisher=Twitte[[Hideo Kojima]] |date=28 March 2013 |accessdate=28 December 2014}}</ref>

While the official trailer announcing the game was running on a PC, the game was released for the seventh and eighth generations of video game consoles. In an interview during E3 2013, when asked about a PC release Kojima stated "We are making it, and it will be on par with the PlayStation 4 and Xbox One versions."<ref name="pc">{{cite web|title=Watch Metal Gear Solid 5's intro to hear Kiefer Sutherland as Snake|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/9/24/4768178/metal-gear-solid-5-ground-zeroes-intro-kiefer-sutherland-snake|publisher=Polygon|date=24 September 2013|accessdate=19 October 2013}}</ref> However, he made it clear that the PC port was not their priority.<ref>{{cite news|title=E3 2013: Kojima Interview|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/lpco6n/metal-gear-solid-v--the-phantom-pain-e3-2013--kojima-interview|first=|last=|work=[[GameTrailers]]|date=12 June 2013|accessdate=25 June 2013}}</ref> Kojima confirmed that the visuals seen in the trailer would look close to those in the final game. He also stated that he would like ''Metal Gear Solid V'' to be his final ''Metal Gear'' game, noting that unlike previous titles where he had announced that he had finished making games in the series, only to return for subsequent games, his involvement with the franchise would be over this time around. Although the trailer had Snake suffering from hallucinations in the form of a flaming whale, Kojima assured that there would be a balance in realism.<ref>{{cite news|title=Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain Kojima Interview|url=http://www.gametrailers.com/videos/84h9k6/metal-gear-solid-v--the-phantom-pain-kojima-interview|first=|last=|work=[[GameTrailers]]|date=28 March 2013|accessdate=29 March 2013}}</ref> Kojima later revealed that ''The Phantom Pain'' was initially presented as an independent game so as to assess the public and industry response to the [[Fox Engine]], as he felt that announcing the game as part of ''Metal Gear Solid V'' would bias reactions to the engine.

On June 10, 2013, at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2013|E3 2013]], a fourth trailer was shown at the [[Microsoft]] press conference, demonstrating the new play mechanics, as well as the cast of characters. The development of an [[Xbox One]] version was also announced at the conference.<ref>{{cite web|title=E3 2013: Metal Gear Solid V Coming To Xbox One|url=http://ca.ign.com/articles/2013/06/10/e3-2013-metal-gear-solid-v-coming-to-xbox-one|publisher=IGN|accessdate=11 June 2013}}</ref>  The [[PlayStation 4]] version was announced the following day when Konami uploaded the red band version of the trailer on their YouTube channel in addition to the standard green band version.<ref>{{cite web|last=Stanyon|first=Matt|title=Metal Gear Solid V E3 2013 Trailer Coming on 12th June 2013|url=http://www.hybridgames.co.uk/metalgearsolid/mgs5/news/e3-2013-trailer-coming-on-12th-june-2013/|publisher=Hybrid Games|accessdate=7 June 2013}}</ref><ref name="konamipress_20130612">{{cite web|url=http://www.konami-digital-entertainment.co.jp/en/news/release/2013/0612/|title=Next-Generation METAL GEAR "METAL GEAR SOLID V: THE PHANTOM PAIN" Cutting-Edge Game Consoles "PlayStation®4" and "Xbox One" Confirmed as Release Platform}}</ref>

The trailers for ''Metal Gear Solid V'' showed the game running on a PC hardware, but according to Kojima with textures and character models somewhat based on [[History of video game consoles (seventh generation)|seventh generation hardware]]. The developers aimed to improve the technical quality for the versions released for the [[History of video game consoles (eighth generation)|eighth generation of consoles]].<ref>{{cite web|last=McWhertor|first=Michael|title=Kojima: Next-gen versions of Metal Gear Solid 5 will look better than E3 trailer|url=http://www.polygon.com/2013/6/13/4425442/next-gen-metal-gear-solid-5-smartphone-tablet-kojima|publisher=Polygon|accessdate=13 June 2013}}</ref>

Kojima alluded to the game possibly being "too big to clear", adding that the game is "200 [times larger] than ''Ground Zeroes''".<ref>{{cite web |last=Dyer |first=Mitch |date=5 March 2014 |url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/03/05/kojima-worried-the-phantom-pain-is-too-big-to-finish |title=Kojima Worried The Phantom Pain Is 'Too Big' to Finish |publisher=IGN |accessdate=5 March 2014}}</ref> Kojima wanted the player to connect with Snake in ''The Phantom Pain''. To accomplish this, the loss of Mother Base, which the player developed throughout ''Peace Walker'', would serve as motivation for revenge for both Snake and the player. Kojima also tried making Snake relatable to newcomers of the series by making him unaware of what happened in the nine years during which he was in a coma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerandvideogames.com/467996/interviews/interview-hideo-kojima-on-darker-themes-and-phantom-cigars/|title=Interview: Hideo Kojima on darker themes and phantom cigars|publisher=Computer and Video Games|author=Mike Jackson|date=2014-06-12|accessdate=25 June 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140817122624/http://www.computerandvideogames.com/467996/interviews/interview-hideo-kojima-on-darker-themes-and-phantom-cigars/|archivedate=2014-08-17}}</ref> Weapons, vehicles and other armaments are unlicensed and fictional in ''The Phantom Pain'', just as they were in ''Ground Zeroes'', unlike previous ''Metal Gear Solid'' games that included mostly real-world based weaponry.

On June 9, 2014, at [[Electronic Entertainment Expo 2014|E3 2014]], a fifth cinematic trailer featuring [[Mike Oldfield]]'s song "[[Man on the Rocks#Singles and promotion|Nuclear]]" was shown at the [[Sony]] press conference, unveiling more plot details surrounding the Diamond Dogs and Snake's antagonistic descent. It was leaked a day earlier, due to an accidental post from Konami's official [[YouTube]] channel.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Plunkett|first1=Luke|title=Metal Gear Solid V's E3 Trailer Isn't Waiting For E3|url=http://kotaku.com/metal-gear-solid-vs-e3-trailer-isnt-waiting-for-e3-1587962381|website=Kotaku|accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref> Alongside the new trailer, the official site for ''Metal Gear Solid V'' was updated and included new information and images such as the developmental progress of the in-game map and the evolution of Snake's design across all games in the series.<ref>{{cite web|title=Progress: ''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Paim'' &mdash; Official Site|url=http://www.konami.jp/mgs5/tpp/en/progress/index.php5|website=Metal Gear Solid V - Official Site|accessdate=10 June 2014}}</ref> On August 25, 2015, Kojima released a launch trailer showing "Metal Gear's Evolution and Harmony" with clips from the previous games along with the reveal of the new "Metal Gear Sahelanthropus".

Over $80 million was spent on the development of the game.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yin-Poole|first1=Wesley|title=New article on Konami paints a bleak picture|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-08-03-new-article-on-konami-paints-a-bleak-picture|website=[[Eurogamer]]|publisher=Gamer Network|accessdate=3 August 2015|date=3 August 2015}}</ref>

=== Music ===
{{Main|Discography of the Metal Gear series#Metal Gear Solid V Original Soundtrack}}

The music of ''The Phantom Pain'' was produced by [[Harry Gregson-Williams]], making it his fourth ''Metal Gear'' title, and composed by Ludvig Forssell, [[Justin Burnett]], and Daniel James. Also featured in ''The Phantom Pain'' are collectable music tapes the player can listen to in-game, with a mixture of licensed music from the era, and music from past ''Metal Gear'' titles.

''Metal Gear Solid V Original Soundtrack'' was released on September 2nd, 2015, containing 50 tracks selected from both ''Ground Zeroes'' and ''The Phantom Pain''. Following this on December 23rd, 2015, was ''Metal Gear Solid V Extended Soundtrack'', containing 114 tracks again selected from both ''Metal Gear Solid V'' games. Finally, ''Metal Gear Solid V Original Soundtrack The Lost Tapes'' was released on March 30th, 2016, primarily consisting of tracks written by Ludvig Forssell for the in-game cassette tapes. The latter two releases also include music that went unused in the game, with ''Metal Gear Solid V Extended Soundtrack'' in particular containing two tracks from the cut ''Mission 51: Kingdom of the Flies''.

The game's soundtrack later won the award for Best Score/Soundtrack at [[The Game Awards 2015]].<ref name="TGA: Nominees"/> The event also had [[Stefanie Joosten]], Quiet's voice actress, on stage performing "Quiet's Theme".

=== Dispute between Konami and Kojima ===
{{Further|Kojima Productions#Closure}}
In March 2015, Konami announced plans for a corporate restructuring that saw them part ways with Hideo Kojima and his development studio Kojima Productions. As part of the separation, Kojima's name was removed from the game cover, all of its associated paraphernalia and future releases of ''Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes'' and ''Metal Gear Solid: The Legacy Collection''.<ref name="kojima credits">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-20-konami-announces-plan-for-brand-new-metal-gear-solid-series|title=Konami announces plan for brand new Metal Gear series|publisher=Eurogamer|last1=Yin-Poole|first1=Wesley|accessdate=20 March 2015}}</ref>{{efn|Gameplay videos have shown Kojima's name included within the game itself, with individual credits sequences for each mission.}} A Konami spokesperson stated that Kojima would still be involved with Konami and the ''Metal Gear'' franchise,<ref name="polygon-kojimaremoved" /> and despite the dispute, the company expressed confidence that the game would be declared [[Game of the Year]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/its-the-game-of-the-year-guaranteed-konami-says-ab/1100-6430162/|title="It's the Game of the Year--Guaranteed," Konami Says About MGS5|last=Makuch|first=Eddie|date=30 August 2015|work=GameSpot|accessdate=30 August 2015}}</ref>

In July 2015, series composer [[Rika Muranaka]] told ''Fragged Nation'' in an interview that over 30 commissioned songs for [[Metal Gear Solid]] were never used, with Muranaka believing that Kojima has a lack of business sense that played a part in his split from Konami.<ref name="MGSV_Music">{{cite news|url=http://nichegamer.com/2015/07/metal-gear-solid-composer-says-hideo-kojima-split-from-konami-over-budget-issues/|title=Metal Gear Solid Composer Says Hideo Kojima Split from Konami Over Budget Issues|first=Brandon|last=Orselli|publisher=[[nichegamer]]|accessdate=21 September 2015|date=31 July 2015}}</ref>

== Release ==
''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'' was released in different editions. Special Day One editions of the game for each platform featured [[downloadable content]] (DLC) vouchers for special weapons and ''Metal Gear Online'' experience points. The North American Collector's Edition (which was available for PS4 and Xbox One) comes with a steelbook and a small-size replica of Snake's bionic arm; the Premium Package for the Japanese release (which was available for PS4, PS3, and Xbox One) features a full-size replica, which was also sold separately in May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sentinel-toys.com/catalog/info.php?target=products_detail&products_id=256 |title=千値練國際有限公司 ー Sentinel International Co., Ltd |website=Sentinel-toys.com |date= |accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref> Sony released a PlayStation 4 bundle with the unit painted in the colors of the arm.

The physical PC release of ''The Phantom Pain'' only includes a CD key and a disc with a [[Steam (software)|Steam]] installer contained within. Game files are not included on-disc and must be downloaded.<ref name="vg247-steamdisc">{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain PC disc only contains Steam installer|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/08/31/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-pc-disc-only-contains-steam-installe|website=VG24/7|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref><ref name="ndtv-pcgaminggettingbetter">{{cite web|title=PC Gaming Is Getting Better, but Publishers Are Getting Worse|url=http://gadgets.ndtv.com/games/opinion/pc-gaming-is-getting-better-but-publishers-are-getting-worse-768606|website=Gadgets 360|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>

Tie-in products were also released for the game. [[Sony Mobile Communications]] released special edition [[Walkman]], [[Sony Xperia Z4|Xperia Z4]], [[Sony Xperia Z3 Tablet Compact|Xperia Z3 Tablet Compact]], and Xperia J Compact devices, each featuring Outer Heaven emblems, soundtrack audio, and wallpapers.<ref name="verge-sonytpp">{{cite web|title=Sony's Metal Gear Solid Walkman is a truly tasteful video game tie-in|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/8/19/9175729/sony-phantom-pain-walkman-tablet-xperia|website=The Verge|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref> Watch manufacturer [[Seiko]] released a digital watch, resembling Venom Snake's watch from the game. Eyeglasses maker JF Rey produced themed eyewear patterned after what Kaz and Ocelot are wearing in the game. Japanese toy company Sentinel, which previously made an iDroid casing for the iPhone 5 and 5S, produced a transformable figure of the [[Sahelanthropus]],<ref>{{cite web|last=Nunneley |first=Stephany |url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/09/25/metal-gear-solid-5-sahelanthropus-figure/ |title=This Metal Gear Sahelanthropus figure is transformable and super cool |website=VG247.com |date=2015-09-25 |accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref> while Kotobukiya readied a 1/100 scale kit of the unit. Sports apparel company Puma joined the project through a line of sports jackets, T-shirts, and footwear, including Snake's sneaking boots.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalgearinformer.com/?p=21478 |title=PUMA MGSV The Phantom Pain shirts, jackets and shoes get new pictures |publisher=Metal Gear Informer |date=2015-08-31 |accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.jp/mgs5/tpp/jp/goods/index.php5 |title=関連グッズ &#124; Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain - 公式Webサイト |website=Konami.jp |date=2013-04-04 |accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref>

Square Enix's PlayArts ''Kai'' figure line featured several of the game's characters, while Kaiyodo produced Venom Snake and a Soviet Army soldier for the RevoMini figure category. An art book, titled ''The Art of Metal Gear Solid V'', was published by [[Dark Horse Comics]] on November 2, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/4/21/11482166/dark-horse-publishing-the-art-of-metal-gear-solid-5-this-november|title=Dark Horse publishing The Art of Metal Gear Solid 5 this November|first=Michael|last=McWhertor|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|date=April 21, 2016|accessdate=April 22, 2016}}</ref>

A complete edition of the game, titled ''Metal Gear Solid V: The Definitive Experience'',{{efn|or ''Metal Gear Solid V: Ground Zeroes + The Phantom Pain'' in Japan}} was released for PlayStation 4, Xbox One and Steam on October 11 in North America, October 13 in Europe, and November 10 in Japan. The bundle includes the ''Ground Zeroes'' prologue and ''The Phantom Pain'' in one package, along with all previously released downloadable content for both games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameinformer.com/b/news/archive/2016/08/29/metal-gear-solid-v-the-definitive-experience-confirmed-coming-in-october.aspx?|title=Metal Gear Solid V: The Definitive Experience Confirmed, Coming In October|first=Javy|last=Gwaltney |date=August 29, 2016|accessdate=August 30, 2016|work=[[Game Informer]]}}</ref>

