}}

''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'' received "universal acclaim" from critics, according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name="MCXONE" /><ref name="MCPS4" /><ref name="MCPC" />

Vince Ingenito of [[IGN]] awarded the game a score of 10/10, complimenting the way the gameplay mechanics worked together and the organic nature of the open-ended missions that allowed players to create their own memorable experiences, without being punished for deviating from stealth. The review concluded that ''The Phantom Pain'' is "a gameplay marvel, rewarding intelligence and creativity in a way few games do."<ref name="IGN" /> [[GameSpot]] also gave the game a 10/10, similarly praising its "near impeccable" gameplay, commenting that, alongside main and side missions, "emergent scenarios serve as the third pillar of ''The Phantom Pain''{{'s}} open-world gameplay experience". The review also highlighted the meaningful development of the characters despite being beholden to the original ''Metal Gear'' as the conclusion of Venom Snake's character arc.<ref name="GSpot" /> ''The Phantom Pain'' was the twenty-third game&mdash;and the third in the ''Metal Gear'' series&mdash;to ever receive a perfect 40/40 review rating from Japanese magazine ''[[Famitsu]]''.<ref name="Famitsu">{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/08/famitsu-review-scores-issue-1395|title=Famitsu Review Scores: Issue 1395|date=August 25, 2015|website=Gematsu}}</ref>

''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'' awarded the game 9.5/10, praising the story's emotional power and thematic concerns exploring the futility of war in a much more compelling and cohesive way than other franchises such as ''[[Call of Duty]]'' and ''[[Battlefield (video game series)|Battlefield]]'', as well as the way in which the game world responded to the player's actions. However, the review was critical of the reliance on resource management, particularly in the way assaults on Forward Operating Bases could interrupt and distract from key missions.<ref name="EGM"/> [[Destructoid]] awarded it a score of 9/10, saying that the game is "equal parts tough and flashy, and it's fitting that if this is Kojima's last ''Metal Gear'', he goes on a high note."<ref name="Destruct" />

''[[Game Informer]]''{{'}}s Joe Juba awarded the game 9.25/10, praising the mission design for its flexibility and offering players multiple pathways to completion without restricting their choice of weapons or equipment. However, despite seeing the value in restructuring the narrative to compliment the open world platform and the episodic mission structure given the series' complex mythology, Juba felt that this went too far with the result being that the player could stumble into crucial story elements without context.<ref name="GI"/> ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]''{{'}}s Michael McWhertor also awarded the game 9/10, similarly praising the game mechanics, but directing criticism at the convoluted storyline which it felt hinged on a detailed knowledge of the series' mythos to the point where it would be inaccessible to newcomers to the franchise.<ref name="polygon" />

''The Phantom Pain'' was also positively received outside the traditional gaming media. In a five-star review, ''[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]''{{'}}s Kirk McKeand stated that the game "takes the best of a great series and creates a series' best in the process". The review complimented the seamless integration of the gameplay modes and noted the way the game's Mother Base mode offered satisfactory and meaningful progress,<ref name="kirk" /> a sentiment echoed by ''[[Time Magazine|Time]]''{{'}}s Matt Peckham,<ref name="time" /> who also complimented the game's longevity, pacing and [[Artificial intelligence (video games)|artificial intelligence]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://time.com/4005807/metal-gear-solid-v-the-phantom-pain-review/|title=After 30 Hours of ''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'', I’m Nowhere Near Finished|first=Matt|last=Peckham|work=time.com|publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|accessdate=29 August 2015|date=23 August 2015}}</ref>

While much of ''The Phantom Pain'' received plaudits, the game was criticized by some reviewers who felt it was lacking in terms of a focused and compelling narrative with interesting characters, especially when compared to prior ''Metal Gear'' titles. Ingenito opined that its story would be divisive for long-term fans, calling it "insubstantial and underdeveloped", with plot-related questions generally being answered in a "rushed and unsatisfying" way and a tendency for the game to gloss over its subject matter. He wrote how much of the characterization and memorable moments seen in previous installments had been replaced with individuals doing little more than appearing in scenes, giving information and then standing around. In addition, he called out the frequent lack of communication from Kiefer Sutherland as Venom Snake throughout important plot sections as "positively jarring".<ref name="IGN" /> ''[[Kotaku]]''{{'}}s Jason Schreier argued that the story was "damn unfulfilling", having "terrible" pacing, "incoherent" dialogue, and "incomprehensible" character motivations. He echoed Ingenito's view of Snake, calling him in cutscenes "nearly silent to the point of awkwardness ... where his response to emotional events will often just be to look at people."<ref name="Kotaku">{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain: The Kotaku Review|url=https://kotaku.com/metal-gear-solid-v-the-phantom-pain-the-kotaku-review-1728728287|website=Kotaku|accessdate=11 January 2018}}</ref> David Roberts, writing for ''[[GamesRadar]]'', described the story as "unconventional" and full of "loosely connected scenes", saying "a whole lot of nothing happens in between quick bursts of exposition". He praised Kiefer Sutherland as Snake, but criticized Skullface as being greatly undeveloped as a villain and being met with "one of the most anti-climactic showdowns in video game history". Roberts also wrote how the story "drifts along aimlessly" in the second half and which ultimately felt "hollow" from not giving closure to the end [[Plot_twist|twist]] that the player is not controlling Big Boss.<ref name="GamesRadar">{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=David|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 is the best and most disappointing game of the year|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/metal-gear-solid-5-best-and-most-disappointing-game-year/|website=GamesRadar+|accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref> Similarly, the reveal and story ending also drew a [[Venom_Snake#Reception|polarizing response from other critics]].

''The Phantom Pain'' was also criticized for forcing players to replay missions on higher difficulty settings to unlock the final missions,<ref name="GSpot" /><ref name="Destruct" /><ref name="IGN" /> with Schreier saying that it added unnecessary padding to a section of plot conveying the game's most emotional events.<ref name="Kotaku" />

=== Portrayal of Quiet ===
{{Main|Quiet (Metal Gear)}}
Before the release of the game, the presentation of the female character Quiet became a topic of controversy concerning her appearance. ''[[Halo (series)|Halo]]'' designer David Ellis criticized her for being [[oversexualized]] and a negative affirmation of the stereotype of the game industry as "full of man babies".<ref name="GameSpot: criticism">{{cite web|title=Kojima addresses criticism over MGSV's 'sexy' Quiet character|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/kojima-addresses-criticism-over-mgsvs-sexy-quiet-characte1100-6414204/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Halo dev calls MGSV female character design "disgusting"|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/halo-dev-calls-mgsv-female-character-design-disgusting/1100-6414137/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2015/9/7/9272995/metal-gear-solid-5-voice-actress-lets-play|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 voice actress is doing a Let's Play of the game|author=|date=|website=polygon.com}}</ref> Kojima and Konami released Quiet figurines in May 2015 as part of the game's promotion. The figure's soft, pliable breasts were criticized in social media and in the press.<ref>{{cite web|last=Phillips |first=Tom |url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-05-11-mgs5s-seedy-quiet-figure-has-squeezable-boobs |title=MGS5's seedy Quiet figure has squeezable boobs |publisher=Eurogamer.net |date=2015-05-11 |accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Parsons|first1=Jeff|title=Seedy Metal Gear Solid action figure will have squeezable boobs|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/technology-science/technology/seedy-metal-gear-solid-action-5691403|website=Mirror|accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://metro.co.uk/2015/05/11/metal-gear-solid-vs-quiet-doll-has-squeezable-breasts-5191651/|title=Metal Gear Solid V's Quiet doll has squeezable breasts|author=|date=11 May 2015|website=metro.co.uk}}</ref>

The finished game drew more criticism of Quiet's portrayal in both reviews and opinion pieces.<ref name="Tamburro">{{cite web|last1=Rouner|first1=Jef|title=There is No 'Smart Reason' for Naked Women in Video Games|url=http://www.houstonpress.com/arts/there-is-no-smart-reason-for-naked-women-in-video-games-7914860|website=Houston Press|accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Tamburro|first1=Paul|title=Let’s Talk About THAT Quiet Scene in Metal Gear Solid|url=http://www.craveonline.com/culture/900837-lets-talk-quiet-scene-metal-gear-solid-v|website=Crave|accessdate=11 January 2016}}</ref> ''[[GamesRadar]]''{{'}}s David Roberts described Quiet as "one of the most complex and conflicted characters in ''MGS5''", but that her depiction was an example of a "juvenile approach to sexuality" that typifies Kojima's work and the ''Metal Gear'' series as a whole.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Roberts|first1=David|title=Quiet embodies Metal Gear's complex relationship with women|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/quiet-embodies-metal-gears-complex-relationship-women/|website=Gamesradar|accessdate=12 January 2016}}</ref> Michael McWhertor of ''Polygon'' described the justification for Quiet's lack of clothing as "inextricably tied to the game's convoluted story", and criticized how the game presented other female characters by "zeroing in on their jiggling breasts and panning across their asses in a silly, oversexualized way."<ref name="polygon"/>

=== Removed content ===
{{Further|Kojima Productions#Closure}}
Following the release of the game, those who had bought the Collector's Edition discovered that the bonus disc included cutscenes and concept art of an in-game mission, "Episode 51: Kingdom of the Flies", that continued on from the end of the campaign, having not been playable in the game. The story ending was criticised for feeling abrupt and leaving several plot points unresolved, and critics found that the removed mission tied up one such important plot thread whilst also providing closure to the relationship between two of the characters. Consequently, many agreed that the inclusion of Episode 51 would have given the game a more satisfactory conclusion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/why-metal-gear-solid-vs-ending-was-so-disappointing-1729833383|title=Why Metal Gear Solid V's Ending Is So Disappointing|last=|first=|date=September 10, 2015|website=Kotaku|publisher=|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/09/07/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-mission-51-cut-content-video/|title=Why was this mission cut from Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain?|website=VG24/7|accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref><ref name="A.V.C">{{cite news|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/without-its-deleted-finale-metal-gear-solid-v-has--242845|title=Without its deleted finale, Metal Gear Solid V has no ending at all|last=Lee|first=Patrick|date=October 19, 2016|work=The A.V. Club|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref name="GamesRadar" />

Another large criticism of the story was the decision to force players to replay past missions to progress through its second half,<ref name="GSpot" /><ref name="Destruct" /><ref name="IGN" /><ref name="Kotaku" /><ref name="GamesRadar" /> with one theory being that original content had been envisioned but which had not been incorporated into the finished game due to time constraints, resulting in the re-used sections.<ref name="Retrospective">{{Cite web|url=http://ichoosetostand.blogspot.co.uk/2016/01/retrospective-metal-gear-solid-v.html|title=Retrospective: Metal Gear Solid V - The Phantom Pain (2015)|last=|first=|date=21 January 2016|website=I Choose To Stand|publisher=|access-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.megabearsfan.net/post/2016/04/11/What-was-Phantom-Pains-second-chapter-supposed-to-be-about.aspx|title=Trying to fit a story onto chapter 2 of MGSV: Phantom Pain|last=|first=|date=April 11, 2016|website=Mega Bears Fan|publisher=|access-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref> This assumption was supported by further evidence of removed content: not long after the discovery of Chapter 51, users of the [[Facepunch Studios|Facepunch]] forums who had been extracting data from the PC version of the game's files found evidence of a third story chapter, titled "Chapter 3: Peace", that was not included in the final version of the game.<ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 The Phantom Pain Is An Unfinished Game, Had A Chapter 3 As Well|url=https://gamingbolt.com/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-is-an-unfinished-game-had-a-chapter-3-as-well|website=Gaming Bolt}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/612967/Metal-Gear-Solid-5-update-Phantom-Pain-DLC-missions-Konami-PS4-Xbox-One|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: Konami give Kojima update as new Phantom Pain mission list revealed|last=Jones|first=Gary|date=October 20, 2015|work=[[Express.co.uk]]|accessdate=July 9, 2016}}</ref> Konami later neither confirmed nor denied that Chapter 3 had been fully cut from the main game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamingbolt.com/metal-gear-solid-5-producer-responds-to-secret-chapter-questions-as-fans-rally-to-unlock-it|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: Producer Responds To Secret Chapter Questions As Fans Rally To "Unlock" It|website=GamingBolt|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref> ''Metal Gear Solid'' community manager Robert Allen Peeler was asked via [[Twitter]] if any upcoming downloadable content would be released for ''The Phantom Pain'', in the hope that the story content would be included, but this was refuted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamingbolt.com/metal-gear-solid-5-story-dlc-not-happening-anytime-soon-revisiting-camp-omega-clarified|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 Story DLC Not Happening Anytime Soon, Revisiting Camp Omega Clarified|website=GamingBolt|accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref> Many fans also believed that, due to the chapter's title, it was somehow linked to Konami's "Nuclear Disarmament Event" which was opened shortly after launch with the goal of revealing a secret in the game, and which would close once all in-game [[nuclear disarmament|nuclear weapons that had been manufactured by players were disposed of]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.konami.jp/mgs5/tpp/en/news/20151126.html|title=The Secret Nuclear Disarmament Event|website=Konami|access-date=2 September 2016}}</ref> Data miners had uncovered a related cutscene within the game's files that would be released once the event had finished,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l4uSkAACoHc|title=Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain - Nuclear Disarmament [Hidden Cutscene]|date=12 September 2015|website=YouTube|access-date=2 September 2016}}</ref> however speculation still spread that Chapter 3 was connected in some way. Robert Allen Peeler discussed player's suspicions via Twitter and Reddit and did not deny that further events may occur once the disarmament had concluded.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gamingbolt.com/mgs-5s-chapter-3-may-be-related-to-nuclear-disarmament-but-konami-wont-trigger-it-manually|title=MGS 5’s Chapter 3 May Be Related To Nuclear Disarmament, But Konami Won’t Trigger It Manually|date=31 August 2016|website=GamingBolt|publisher=Pramath|access-date=2 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.reddit.com/NeverBeGameOvecomments/50e1m0/regarding_peelers_comments_on_chapter_3/|title=Regarding Peeler's comments on chapter 3|date=31 August 2016|website=Reddit|access-date=2 September 2016}}</ref> On February 2, 2018, the Nuclear Disarmament Event ending was triggered prematurely on the Steam version of the game, despite there still being over 9000 player nukes in existence at the time, resulting in the release of the previously-uncovered cutscene.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Alexandra|first1=Heather|title=After Years of Player Warfare, Metal Gear Solid V Secret Ending Triggered Prematurely|url=https://kotaku.com/metal-gear-solid-v-s-nuclear-disarmament-ending-was-tri-1822742864|website=Kotaku|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Hall|first1=Charlie|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 celebrates nuclear disarmament, but it’s a bug|url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/2/5/16974544/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-nuclear-disarmament-cutscene-donald-trump-doomsday-clock|website=Polygon|accessdate=7 February 2018}}</ref> After investigation, Konami announced that this was the result of a technical error owing to the game's servers being sent incorrect values.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vincent|first1=Brittany|title=The Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain Disarmament Was a Glitch After All|url=http://twinfinite.net/2018/02/the-metal-gear-solid-v-the-phantom-pain-disarmament-was-a-glitch-after-all/|website=Twinfinite|accessdate=15 February 2018}}</ref>

Critics attributed the missing content to the disclosed tensions between Konami and Kojima during development, the general consensus being that Konami had given strict deadlines for the game's release, having been dissatisfied with how much money Kojima had spent on development.<ref name="Retrospective" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/one-of-metal-gear-solid-vs-most-important-story-scenes-1728467641|title=One Of Metal Gear Solid V's Most Important Story Scenes Was Cut|website=Kotaku|accessdate=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref name="Kotaku" /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Carter|first1=Chris|title=So, let's talk about Metal Gear Solid V's ending|url=https://www.destructoid.com/so-let-s-talk-about-metal-gear-solid-v-s-ending-311489.phtml|website=Destructoid}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Leack|first1=Jonathan|title=An Incomplete MGSV: The Phantom Pain Offers Clue to Why Kojima Was Let Go by Konami|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/features/11744-an-incomplete-mgsv-the-phantom-pain-offers-clue-to-why-kojima-was-let-go-by-konami#/slide/1|website=Game Revolution|accessdate=12 February 2018}}</ref> Data miners also uncovered numerous other examples of lesser content that had not been included in the game, ranging from gameplay features to cutscenes, but what precisely had been removed as a result of the Konami-Kojima conflict, and what had simply been abandoned earlier in development out of choice, was open to discussion.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Shabana Arif|title=This is what the missing content from MGS5: The Phantom Pain looks like|url=https://www.vg247.com/2015/09/22/this-is-what-the-missing-content-from-mgs5-the-phantom-pain-looks-like/#below-article|website=VG24/7}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=How Much Was Cut from Metal Gear Solid 5?|url=https://gamerant.com/metal-gear-solid-5-story-cuts-512/|website=Gamerant.com|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Metal Gear Solid V: Every Piece Of Cut Content You Need To See|url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/metal-gear-solid-v-every-piece-of-cut-content-you-need-to-see|website=whatculture.com|accessdate=8 June 2017}}</ref> Regardless, due to the removed story content and subsequent narrative flaws, the game was labeled by some critics as being unfinished.<ref name="Retrospective" /><ref name="Kotaku" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2015/09/17/5-questions-i-have-after-beating-metal-gear-solid-v-the-phantom-pain/|title=5 questions I have after beating Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain|last=|first=|date=September 15, 2015|website=VentureBeat|publisher=|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-09-19-metal-gear-solid-5-the-unfinished-swan-song|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The unfinished swan song|last=|first=|date=September 22, 2015|website=Eurogamer|publisher=|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Rashid Sayed|title=Konami And Kojima Need To Give Answers Regarding Cut Content In Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain|url=https://gamingbolt.com/konami-and-kojima-need-to-give-answers-regarding-cut-content-in-metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain|website=Gaming Bolt}}</ref> Conversely, ''[[GamesRadar]]'' argued that the game's incomplete state was deliberate on Kojima's part.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gamesradar.com/mgs5-unfinished-s-entirely-point/|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 is unfinished? That's entirely the point|last=|first=|date=September 21, 2015|website=GamesRadar+|publisher=|access-date=February 2, 2017}}</ref> Speaking to [[IGN]], Kojima himself seemingly alluded to the fact that he considered the game unfinished when stating that the new intellectual property he was developing since leaving Konami (later revealed as ''[[Death Stranding]]'') would be "a complete game".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.craveonline.co.uk/entertainment/935005-hideo-kojima-suggests-metal-gear-solid-v-unfinished|title=Hideo Kojima Suggests That Metal Gear Solid V WAS Unfinished|last=|first=|date=December 17, 2015|website=Crave Online|publisher=|access-date=February 3, 2017}}</ref>

After the announcement of ''Metal Gear Solid V: The Definitive Experience'', which would include all previously released downloadable content, several fans took this as an opportunity to voice their concerns via Twitter about the missing content that had been uncovered, particularly with regards to Episode 51. Konami responded that Episode 51 had been removed in the early development stages of the game as it had not been intended to be a pivotal ending to the story, and that there were no future plans to have the mission available to play.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/8/31/12733180/metal-gear-solid-5-mission-51-ending|title=Konami says MGS5's ending isn't missing, so everyone can calm down about it|date=31 August 2016|website=Polygon|publisher=Allegra Frank|access-date=2 September 2016}}</ref>

=== Sales ===
''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'' shipped 3 million physical copies within its first five days of release, across all platforms.<ref name="Sales">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/metal-gear-solid-5-sells-3-million-copies-most-of-them-on-playstation-4-10490048.html|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 sells 3 million copies — most of them on PlayStation 4|first=Andrew|last=Griffin|work=[[The Independent]]|date=September 7, 2015|accessdate=7 September 2015}}</ref> On its release date, the game grossed [[United States dollar|US$]]179 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/metal-gear-solid-v-s-opening-day-beats-jurassic-world-avengers-combined-315459.phtml |title=Metal Gear Solid V's opening day beats Jurassic World, Avengers combined |website=Destructoid.com |date=2015-10-14 |accessdate=2015-12-22}}</ref> ''The Phantom Pain'' debuted at number one on the [[United Kingdom]] charts. It became the third biggest video game launch of 2015 in the UK, behind ''[[Batman: Arkham Knight]]'' and ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]''.<ref name="UK_Sales"/> ''The Phantom Pain'' was the most successful launch for the series in the UK, beating the previous record holder, ''[[Metal Gear Solid 2: Sons of Liberty]]'', by 37 percent.<ref name="UK_Sales">{{cite news|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-09-07-metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-is-series-biggest-uk-launch|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain is series' biggest UK launch|first=Tom|last=Phillips|work=eurogamer.net|publisher=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=7 September 2015|date=7 September 2015}}</ref> The game sold 411,199 physical retail copies on PlayStation 3 and PlayStation 4 within the first week of release in Japan, topping the Japanese software sales charts that week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gematsu.com/2015/09/media-create-sales-83115-9615|title=Media Create Sales: 8/31/15 – 9/6/15|date=September 9, 2015|website=Gematsu}}</ref>

The game sold noticeably more on the PlayStation family of consoles than the competing Xbox in the UK. Excluding computer sales, ''The Phantom Pain'' moved approximately 72 percent of copies on PlayStation 4, roughly three times the amount sold on the Xbox One, which accounted for 22 percent of sales. 3 percent of sales were on PlayStation 3, and 2 percent on Xbox 360.<ref name="PS4_OutSold">{{cite news|url=http://www.destructoid.com/metal-gear-solid-5-sells-three-times-more-copies-on-ps4-than-xbox-one-309625.phtml|title=Metal Gear Solid 5 sells three times more copies on PS4 than Xbox One|first=Nikki|last=Blake|work=destructoid.com|publisher=[[Destructoid]]|accessdate=7 September 2015|date=7 September 2015}}</ref> By the end of September 2015, ''Metal Gear Solid V: The Phantom Pain'' had shipped 5 million copies,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.konami.co.jp/en/iir-data/meeting/2015/1030_355711.pdf|title=FY2016 2nd Quarter Financial Results|publisher=Konami|accessdate=October 30, 2015}}{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and reached 6 million by the end of December 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Passalacqua|first1=Michael|title=Metal Gear Solid 5: The Phantom Pain Shipped Over 6 Million Copies|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2016/01/29/metal-gear-solid-5-the-phantom-pain-shipped-over-6-million-copies|publisher=IGN|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref>

